SHE&rsquo;S only 20 years old but gospel singer Siphokazi Oyiya already has two albums under her belt.She told Daily Sun: &ldquo;I recorded my first album called Hamba Gideon in 2010. I was only 13 years old.&ldquo;Ever since then, I have shared the stage with the best of Mzansi gospel artists such as Sipho Makhabane, Butho and Yolanda Vuthela.&rdquo;Siphokazi&rsquo;s second album, Akukapheli, came in 2012.She started her musical journey at a young age. She began singing in the church choir with her mum Nonceba. &ldquo;That&rsquo;s how my love of singing developed. I also sang at school for pupils at Siphamandla High School every Monday.&rdquo; The softly spoken artist from Khayelitsha, Cape Town said after a long absence she is ready to make her mark in the industry.&ldquo;I chose to focus on my studies but now I&rsquo;m ready to reclaim my rightful place. &ldquo;I&rsquo;m going to launch my single called Qoqo on 27 May at the Believers Centre Church in Khayelitsha. &ldquo;I want to show my fans that I&rsquo;m back,&rdquo; she said, adding that she will release her third album in September. Speaking about her experiences as a young singer, Siphokazi said: &ldquo;It&rsquo;s a motivating factor because teenagers and the youth look up to me. &ldquo;They want to be like me.&ldquo;This pushes me to work even harder. Whenever I meet kids, I always tell them to stay away from drugs and to believe in themselves and what they can do to achieve their dreams.&rdquo;